---
import FridayHarborLayout from '../../layouts/FridayHarborLayout.astro';
import { entries } from '../../data/friday-harbor';
const entry = entries.find(e => e.slug === '2026-04-17-does-ai-know-your-city')!;
---
<FridayHarborLayout entry={entry}>
  <figure slot="figure" class="memory-figure">
    <div class="memory-stage" id="stage" aria-label="Two side-by-side maps comparing real Seattle neighborhood boundaries with the boundaries GPT-5.5 Thinking drew from its own internal model">
      <div class="memory-panel">
        <h3 class="memory-panel-title" data-lang="en">Real Seattle <small>· Neighborhood Map Atlas, 94 sub-hoods · framed to the real city</small></h3>
        <h3 class="memory-panel-title" data-lang="zh">真实西雅图 <small>· 邻里地图集，94 个子片区 · 按城市自身范围出图</small></h3>
        <svg class="memory-svg" id="svgReal" viewBox="0 0 480 560" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet" role="img"></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="memory-panel">
        <h3 class="memory-panel-title" data-lang="en">From its own model <small>· GPT-5.5 Thinking, 73 polygons · framed to fit ALL the model drew</small></h3>
        <h3 class="memory-panel-title" data-lang="zh">凭自己的建模画的 <small>· GPT-5.5 Thinking，73 个多边形 · 按模型自身范围出图</small></h3>
        <svg class="memory-svg" id="svgAI" viewBox="0 0 480 560" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet" role="img"></svg>
      </div>
      <p class="map-status" id="status">
        <span data-lang="en">Loading boundaries...</span>
        <span data-lang="zh">边界加载中...</span>
      </p>
    </div>

    <figcaption data-lang="en">
      <b>Left: the real Seattle, framed to its actual bounds. Right: the entire city the model drew, framed to fit all of it.</b>
      We deliberately let the right panel zoom out — what the model imagined extends well past the real city, so we show all of it. Only the
      eight neighborhoods where the deviation is the headline get labelled: red where the model bloats one, green where it shrinks one. The
      same eight are highlighted in the same colours on the left, so each red shape on the left has a matching red label on the right.
      <span class="legend-line">
        <span class="legend-swatch swatch-bloat"></span>
        <span><b>Bloat</b> — drawn much larger than reality. The label carries the multiplier.</span>
      </span>
      <span class="legend-line">
        <span class="legend-swatch swatch-shrink"></span>
        <span><b>Shrink</b> — drawn smaller than reality. The label carries the multiplier.</span>
      </span>
    </figcaption>

    <figcaption data-lang="zh">
      <b>左：真实西雅图，按城市自身的范围出图。右：模型脑里画出的整座城，按它自己的范围出图。</b>
      右图我们刻意放大视野——模型想象出的西雅图比真城大得多，与其裁掉一半，不如让它全部显示。只在八个分歧最显著的邻里上做标签：
      红色是模型把这个邻里画大了，绿色是画小了。同样这八个，左图用同样的颜色高亮——左侧的每一块红，对应右侧同名的红色标注。
      <span class="legend-line">
        <span class="legend-swatch swatch-bloat"></span>
        <span><b>膨胀</b>——画得比真实大很多，标注上写的是倍数。</span>
      </span>
      <span class="legend-line">
        <span class="legend-swatch swatch-shrink"></span>
        <span><b>压缩</b>——画得比真实小，标注上写的是倍数。</span>
      </span>
    </figcaption>

    <aside class="memory-stats" aria-label="key bias figures">
      <div class="stat" data-lang="en">
        <span class="stat-num">1.9<small>&nbsp;×</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">AI Seattle is nearly twice the city's area (408 vs 216 km²)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat" data-lang="zh">
        <span class="stat-num">1.9<small>&nbsp;倍</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">AI 画的西雅图面积近真实城市两倍（408 vs 216 平方公里）</span>
      </div>

      <div class="stat" data-lang="en">
        <span class="stat-num">52<small>&nbsp;%</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">of the AI's polygons fall inside the real city; the other half spills out</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat" data-lang="zh">
        <span class="stat-num">52<small>&nbsp;%</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">AI 画出的图仅一半落在真实西雅图内，另一半溢出到城外</span>
      </div>

      <div class="stat" data-lang="en">
        <span class="stat-num">0<small>&nbsp;%</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">typical overlap between an AI neighborhood and its real namesake — most don't touch at all</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat" data-lang="zh">
        <span class="stat-num">0<small>&nbsp;%</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">AI 邻里与同名真实邻里的典型重叠率 —— 多数情况完全不相交</span>
      </div>

      <div class="stat" data-lang="en">
        <span class="stat-num">3.7<small>&nbsp;km</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">median centroid shift — neighborhoods themselves are typically 1–2 km across</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat" data-lang="zh">
        <span class="stat-num">3.7<small>&nbsp;公里</small></span>
        <span class="stat-label">质心位移中位数 —— 一个邻里本身通常只有 1–2 公里宽</span>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <details class="memory-prompt-box">
      <summary><span data-lang="en">The exact prompt given to the model</span><span data-lang="zh">给模型的原始提示词</span></summary>
      <pre class="memory-prompt">Generate a GeoJSON FeatureCollection of Seattle neighborhoods from memory only. Draw detailed polygon boundaries for each neighborhood as accurately as possible. Add metadata stating the boundaries are approximate and not authoritative.</pre>
      <p class="memory-prompt-note" data-lang="en">No tools, no web access, no system prompt steering toward a source. The model returned 73 polygons and self-tagged the file <code>generated_from_memory_only: true</code>, <code>authoritative: false</code>.</p>
      <p class="memory-prompt-note" data-lang="zh">未联网、未调用任何工具、系统提示也未导向任何数据源。模型给出 73 个多边形，并自行在文件元数据里标注 <code>generated_from_memory_only: true</code>、<code>authoritative: false</code>。</p>
    </details>
  </figure>

  <div slot="notebook-en">
    <p>
      On April 17, 2026, the most capable "thinking" model in OpenAI's
      current line — which self-identifies in its output as
      <em>GPT-5.5 Thinking</em> — was given the prompt above and no tools.
      Just: draw Seattle's neighborhoods, from its own internal model of the city. It returned 73
      named polygons, attached metadata saying the boundaries were
      "approximate and not authoritative," and exited gracefully.
    </p>
    <p>
      The map it drew is <em>twice</em> the size of the city. The 73
      polygons cover 408 km²; the real Neighborhood Map Atlas covers 216.
      The AI's Seattle does include the actual Seattle — its union
      overlaps 98 % of the real city — but only about half of what the
      model drew falls inside the real city. The other half is Puget
      Sound, the lake, neighboring suburbs, or invented land beyond
      King County.
    </p>
    <p>
      Per neighborhood, the dissonance gets sharper. Of 64 name-matched
      pairs, more than half the time the model's polygon for a given
      neighborhood does not overlap the real one <em>at all</em>. The
      model knows the rough north-to-south order; it does not know
      where any one neighborhood stops.
    </p>
    <p>
      What this map actually plots is <b>discourse density</b>.
      An AI's resolution of a place is a function of how much was
      written about it. The neighborhoods drawn boldly here are the
      ones the language pays attention to — <b>Ballard</b>, the
      loudest neighborhood on the Seattle internet, drawn 9.3 ×
      too big; <b>High Point</b>, a West Seattle housing-policy
      keyword, 8.4 ×; <b>Crown Hill</b>, 6.8 ×. The ones that
      shrink or get swallowed are the ones the language has not
      paid attention to — <b>Wedgwood</b>, 0.56 ×; <b>Sand Point</b>,
      0.59 ×, the name half-eaten by the older naval base;
      <b>Interbay</b>, 0.64 ×, a working strip the city itself
      never quite labels. The model is doing what a language-trained
      memory should: how much was said about a place becomes how
      much space it gets on the map.
    </p>
    <p class="aside">
      The interesting object here is not the error — it is the <em>shape</em>
      of the error. Visibility <em>in language</em>, not visibility on
      the ground, is what such a model will return. When a chatbot,
      a search summary, or a generative map is asked to "show Seattle"
      to a reader who has never been here, this is the city it draws.
      That distance, in cartographic terms, is bias; in humanistic-GIS
      terms, it is the city's <em>palimpsest of attention</em> — made
      visible because a model with no training on land was made to
      sketch the place from words alone.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div slot="notebook-zh">
    <p>
      2026 年 4 月 17 日，我们给 OpenAI 当下最强的「思考」模型——
      它在元数据里自报为 <em>GPT-5.5 Thinking</em> —— 上面那条
      原始提示词，并明确不允许联网或调用任何工具：
      凭它自己对城市的建模，把西雅图所有邻里的边界尽量画出来。
      它干净利落地给出 73 个命名多边形，附上「边界为近似、非权威」的
      元数据，关闭对话。
    </p>
    <p>
      它画出的西雅图，面积是真实西雅图的<em>两倍</em>。
      73 个多边形合起来 408 平方公里，权威的《邻里地图集》是 216。
      模型的范围确实涵盖了真实西雅图 98% 的地，
      但它画出的图只有约一半落在真实西雅图境内；另一半飘到了普吉特湾里、湖里、邻郊、或干脆是金县外凭空多出来的土地。
    </p>
    <p>
      逐个邻里看，差距更刺眼。能一一配上名字的 64 对里，
      <em>多于一半</em>的情形，模型画出的某邻里与真实同名邻里
      完全没有交集。模型大致知道这些邻里从北到南的排列顺序，
      却不知道任何一个的边界停在哪里。
    </p>
    <p>
      这张图实际画出来的，是<b>讨论的密度</b>。
      AI 对一个地方的分辨率，是这个地方被写过多少的函数。
      被画得最大胆的，都是语言里反复出现的：
      <b>Ballard</b>——西雅图互联网上最热的街区——画到了
      9.3 倍；<b>High Point</b>——美国公共住房政策写作的关键词
      ——8.4 倍；<b>Crown Hill</b> 6.8 倍。
      被压缩或被吞掉的，都是语言里失声的：
      <b>Wedgwood</b> 0.56 倍；<b>Sand Point</b> 0.59 倍——
      名字被同名军用基地吃掉了一半语义；<b>Interbay</b>
      0.64 倍——这片工业带连市政自己都没怎么命名。
      模型做的，正是一台语言训练出的记忆机器该做的事：
      <b>每个地方被写过多少，就被它换算成在地图上获得多少空间</b>。
    </p>
    <p class="aside">
      这里值得读的不是错误本身，而是<em>错误的形状</em>。
      模型最终画出的，是<em>语言世界里能见度高</em>的城市，
      不是地面上的西雅图。
      当一台聊天机器、一段搜索摘要、或一张生成式地图被一个从未来过的读者用来「看西雅图」，
      它返回给读者的就是这个版本——
      它语料里被反复描写的那个城市，不是这座城市本身。
      两者之间的距离，在制图学里就是 bias；
      在人文 GIS 的语言里，是这座城市的「被关注度」留下的<em>重写本</em>——
      只有当一个完全不懂土地的模型被迫只用语言画它时，
      这层重写本才被显形。
    </p>
  </div>

  <ul slot="provenance-en">
    <li>AI-generated polygons: <em>GPT-5.5 Thinking</em> via the prompt shown verbatim under the maps. Single-shot, no tools, no web. The model self-tagged the FeatureCollection <code>generated_from_memory_only: true</code>, <code>authoritative: false</code>. File: <code>docs/seattle_neighborhoods_from_memory_detailed_polygons.geojson</code>.</li>
    <li>Authoritative boundaries: City of Seattle Open Data — <a href="https://data-seattlecitygis.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/SeattleCityGIS::neighborhood-map-atlas-neighborhoods/explore" rel="noopener"><em>Neighborhood Map Atlas</em> (sub-neighborhoods)</a>. 94 polygons. Downloaded 2026-04-17.</li>
    <li>Method: WGS84 → UTM Zone 10N (EPSG:32610) reprojection before any metric computation. Per-neighborhood overlap, area ratio, and centroid distance — measured in metres. Names joined by exact match with a small hand-edited alias table for cases where the model lumps two sub-hoods (e.g. <em>Chinatown-International District</em> → <em>International District</em>) or uses an L_HOOD label. 64 of the 73 model polygons matched a sub-hood; 9 were unmatched and excluded from per-name metrics. The fixed AI geometry served to the page (under <code>public/data/</code>) was repaired with <code>shapely.make_valid + buffer(0)</code>; properties unchanged. The original model output is preserved in <code>docs/seattle_neighborhoods_from_memory_detailed_polygons.geojson</code>.</li>
    <li>9 model labels with no atlas match — the model invented or merged: <em>Lower Queen Anne / Uptown</em>, <em>Madison Valley</em>, <em>Chinatown-International District</em>, <em>Central District</em>, <em>Judkins Park</em>, <em>Hillman City</em>, <em>Othello</em>, <em>Admiral</em>, <em>West Seattle Junction</em>. Several are real Seattle place-names; none correspond to single sub-hoods in the atlas.</li>
    <li>34 atlas sub-hoods with no model entry — the model omitted: <em>Atlantic, Briarcliff, Broadway, Central Business District, Industrial District, Montlake, Pike-Market, Portage Bay,</em> et al. Notable: the Central Business District (downtown's actual name in the atlas) and Montlake (a high-profile neighborhood) are absent.</li>
    <li>Source map &amp; analysis script: <code>src/pages/friday-harbor/2026-04-17-does-ai-know-your-city.astro</code>; comparison written into <code>public/data/seattle_neighborhoods_compare.json</code>.</li>
  </ul>

  <ul slot="provenance-zh">
    <li>AI 生成多边形：<em>GPT-5.5 Thinking</em>，提示词原文已贴在地图下方。一次性调用，未联网、未调用任何工具。模型在 FeatureCollection 元数据里自标 <code>generated_from_memory_only: true</code>、<code>authoritative: false</code>。文件：<code>docs/seattle_neighborhoods_from_memory_detailed_polygons.geojson</code>。</li>
    <li>权威边界：西雅图市政开放数据《<a href="https://data-seattlecitygis.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/SeattleCityGIS::neighborhood-map-atlas-neighborhoods/explore" rel="noopener">邻里地图集</a>》子片区层（sub-neighborhoods），共 94 个多边形。下载日期 2026-04-17。</li>
    <li>方法：先把所有几何重投影到 UTM 10N（EPSG:32610）以米为单位，再逐个邻里测量重叠率、面积比、质心距离。名字用精确匹配；少数情况下模型把两个子片区合成一个或用大片区标签的，靠手工别名表对齐（如 <em>Chinatown-International District</em> → <em>International District</em>）。73 个模型多边形中 64 个对上 sub-hood；9 个无匹配，未参与逐项统计。供页面渲染的 AI 几何（<code>public/data/</code> 下的副本）经过 <code>shapely.make_valid + buffer(0)</code> 修复（修了 4 处 self-intersection），属性不变；模型原始输出保留在 <code>docs/seattle_neighborhoods_from_memory_detailed_polygons.geojson</code>。</li>
    <li>9 个模型自创或合并的标签：<em>Lower Queen Anne / Uptown</em>、<em>Madison Valley</em>、<em>Chinatown-International District</em>、<em>Central District</em>、<em>Judkins Park</em>、<em>Hillman City</em>、<em>Othello</em>、<em>Admiral</em>、<em>West Seattle Junction</em>。多数是西雅图实际存在的地名，但没有任何一个对应到地图集里某一个子片区。</li>
    <li>34 个权威子片区被模型整个漏掉，包括 <em>Atlantic、Briarcliff、Broadway、Central Business District（即真正的市中心商业区）、Industrial District、Montlake、Pike-Market、Portage Bay</em> 等。其中 CBD 和 Montlake 的缺席尤其值得注意。</li>
    <li>源代码与比较脚本：<code>src/pages/friday-harbor/2026-04-17-does-ai-know-your-city.astro</code>；比较结果落盘在 <code>public/data/seattle_neighborhoods_compare.json</code>。</li>
  </ul>
</FridayHarborLayout>

<style>
  .memory-figure { margin: 0; }
  .memory-stage {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
    position: relative;
  }
  .memory-panel {
    background: var(--bg-card, #f5efe2);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule, #d6cdbf);
    padding: 0.7rem 0.7rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .memory-panel-title {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-style: italic;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--uw-purple, #4A2F82);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule, #d6cdbf);
    padding-bottom: 0.35rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.005em;
  }
  .memory-panel-title small {
    display: block;
    font-style: normal;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--ink-faint, #98907f);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-top: 2px;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .memory-svg {
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 480 / 560;
    display: block;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .map-status {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink-faint);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .map-status.is-done { display: none; }

  /* Caption legend swatches */
  .legend-line {
    display: block;
    margin-top: 0.4rem;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
  }
  .legend-swatch {
    display: inline-block;
    width: 14px; height: 14px;
    margin-right: 6px;
    vertical-align: -2px;
    border: 1px solid #888;
  }
  .swatch-real   { background: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.18); border-color: #4A2F82; }
  .swatch-ai     { background: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.18); border-color: #4A2F82; }
  .swatch-bloat  { background: rgba(195, 84, 60, 0.28); border-color: #a13d2a; }
  .swatch-shrink { background: rgba(70, 110, 90, 0.26); border-color: #2f6b54; }

  /* Figcaption shared */
  .memory-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.9rem;
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink, #2c2823);
    /* width inherited from the layout's global figcaption rule */
  }
  .memory-figure figcaption b { font-weight: 600; }

  /* Stats aside — same register as other entries */
  .memory-stats {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 0.8rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 0.6rem;
    padding: 0.8rem 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule, #d6cdbf);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule, #d6cdbf);
  }
  .stat {
    display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 4px;
  }
  .stat-num {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 1.6rem;
    color: var(--uw-purple-deep, #3b1f6b);
    line-height: 1;
  }
  .stat-num small {
    font-size: 0.7em;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--ink-soft, #6c6358);
    margin-left: 2px;
  }
  .stat-label {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
    color: var(--ink-soft, #6c6358);
  }

  /* Prompt block */
  .memory-prompt-box {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem;
    background: var(--bg-card, #f5efe2);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule, #d6cdbf);
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }
  .memory-prompt-box[open] { padding-bottom: 0.9rem; }
  .memory-prompt-box summary {
    cursor: pointer;
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--uw-purple, #4A2F82);
  }
  .memory-prompt {
    margin: 0.6rem 0 0.4rem;
    padding: 0.7rem 0.85rem;
    background: #fffdf7;
    border: 1px dashed var(--rule, #d6cdbf);
    border-radius: 3px;
    font-family: ui-monospace, "SFMono-Regular", Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--ink, #2c2823);
    white-space: pre-wrap;
    word-break: break-word;
  }
  .memory-prompt-note {
    margin: 0.4rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--ink-soft, #6c6358);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  .memory-prompt-note code {
    background: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.06);
    padding: 1px 4px;
    border-radius: 2px;
    font-size: 0.92em;
  }

  /* Both panels share one purple palette so the eye compares SHAPES.
     Real polygons tile cleanly, so a 0.16 alpha reads as a continuous
     city. AI polygons overlap heavily (the model has no shared-edge
     constraint), so their alpha is dropped to 0.06 to keep stacked
     overlaps from going navy. The stroke is the carrier of shape. */
  :global(.nh-real) {
    fill: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.16);
    stroke: #4A2F82;
    stroke-width: 0.6;
    stroke-linejoin: round;
  }
  :global(.nh-ai) {
    fill: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.06);
    stroke: #4A2F82;
    stroke-width: 0.7;
    stroke-linejoin: round;
  }
  /* Bloat / shrink semantic — applied to BOTH panels so the eye can
     trace the same red shape on the left to its red chip on the right. */
  :global(.nh-real.is-bloat),
  :global(.nh-ai.is-bloat) {
    fill: rgba(195, 84, 60, 0.32);
    stroke: #a13d2a;
    stroke-width: 0.9;
  }
  :global(.nh-real.is-shrink),
  :global(.nh-ai.is-shrink) {
    fill: rgba(70, 110, 90, 0.30);
    stroke: #2f6b54;
    stroke-width: 0.9;
  }
  /* Highlight chips — solid pills (no halo). One pill for the multiplier,
     one pill for the name. Both pills are filled with the bias colour and
     all text reads in white, so labels stay legible against any underlying
     polygon density. */
  :global(.nh-chip-pill) {
    stroke-width: 0.9;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip.is-bloat .nh-chip-pill.is-mult) {
    fill: #a13d2a;
    stroke: #6e2818;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip.is-shrink .nh-chip-pill.is-mult) {
    fill: #2f6b54;
    stroke: #1d4a3a;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip.is-bloat .nh-chip-pill.is-name) {
    fill: rgba(255, 253, 247, 0.96);
    stroke: #a13d2a;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip.is-shrink .nh-chip-pill.is-name) {
    fill: rgba(255, 253, 247, 0.96);
    stroke: #2f6b54;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip-num) {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 9.5px;
    fill: #fff;
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip-name) {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-style: italic;
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 9.5px;
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  :global(.nh-chip.is-bloat .nh-chip-name)  { fill: #6e2818; }
  :global(.nh-chip.is-shrink .nh-chip-name) { fill: #1d4a3a; }

  /* Carto furniture */
  :global(.inset-bg) {
    fill: rgba(120, 150, 175, 0.22);
    stroke: var(--ink-faint, #98907f);
    stroke-width: 0.8;
  }
  :global(.inset-grat) {
    fill: none;
    stroke: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.20);
    stroke-width: 0.4;
  }
  :global(.inset-land) {
    fill: rgba(245, 239, 226, 0.95);
    stroke: rgba(74, 47, 130, 0.55);
    stroke-width: 0.4;
  }
  :global(.inset-sphere) {
    fill: none;
    stroke: var(--ink-faint, #98907f);
    stroke-width: 0.8;
  }
  :global(.inset-dot) {
    fill: #a13d2a;
    stroke: #fffdf7;
    stroke-width: 0.8;
  }
  :global(.inset-halo) {
    fill: none;
    stroke: rgba(161, 61, 42, 0.45);
    stroke-width: 0.7;
  }
  :global(.scale-bar .sb-rule) {
    stroke: var(--ink, #2c2823);
    stroke-width: 1.1;
  }
  :global(.scale-bar .sb-tick) {
    stroke: var(--ink, #2c2823);
    stroke-width: 0.9;
  }
  :global(.scale-bar .sb-label) {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 8.5px;
    fill: var(--ink, #2c2823);
  }
  :global(.scale-bar .sb-mid) {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 7.5px;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    fill: var(--ink-faint, #98907f);
  }
  :global(.north-arrow .na-tri) {
    fill: var(--ink, #2c2823);
    stroke: none;
  }
  :global(.north-arrow .na-n) {
    font-family: var(--serif), Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 10px;
    fill: var(--ink, #2c2823);
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .memory-stage { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .memory-stats { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
  }
</style>

<script type="module">
  import * as d3 from 'https://esm.sh/d3@7';

  const REAL_URL    = '/data/seattle_neighborhoods_real.geojson';
  const AI_URL      = '/data/seattle_neighborhoods_ai.geojson';
  // Tiny world land file for the single locator inset (small download).
  const WORLD_URL   = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/martynafford/natural-earth-geojson@master/110m/physical/ne_110m_land.json';

  // The eight neighborhoods where the model's deviation is the headline.
  // These — and only these — get chips on each panel.
  const AI_BLOAT  = { 'Ballard': 9.3, 'High Point': 8.4, 'Crown Hill': 6.8, 'West Seattle Junction': 6.7 };
  const AI_SHRINK = { 'Wedgwood': 0.56, 'Sand Point': 0.59, 'North Beacon Hill': 0.59, 'Interbay': 0.64 };

  // Mirror highlights: atlas S_HOODs that correspond to the model's labels.
  // "West Seattle Junction" is the model's free-form name for the area
  // whose atlas S_HOOD is Genesee; the rest match directly.
  const REAL_BLOAT  = { 'Ballard': 'Ballard', 'High Point': 'High Point', 'Crown Hill': 'Crown Hill', 'Genesee': 'West Seattle Junction' };
  const REAL_SHRINK = { 'Wedgwood': 'Wedgwood', 'Sand Point': 'Sand Point', 'North Beacon Hill': 'North Beacon Hill', 'Interbay': 'Interbay' };
  // Display name on the LEFT chip — using the model's label so the eye can
  // pair "the Ballard chip on the left" with "the Ballard chip on the right"
  // even when the atlas name differs (Genesee → West Seattle Junction).
  const REAL_DISPLAY = REAL_BLOAT;
  const REAL_DISPLAY_S = REAL_SHRINK;

  let _world = null;
  Promise.all([
    fetch(REAL_URL).then(r => r.json()),
    fetch(AI_URL).then(r => r.json()),
    fetch(WORLD_URL).then(r => r.ok ? r.json() : null).catch(() => null),
  ]).then(([real, ai, world]) => {
    _world = world;
    document.getElementById('status')?.classList.add('is-done');
    drawPanels(real, ai);
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => drawPanels(real, ai), { passive: true });
  }).catch(err => {
    const s = document.getElementById('status');
    if (s) s.innerHTML = '<span>Map data failed to load — showing text only.</span>';
    console.error(err);
  });

  function drawPanels(real, ai) {
    const svgReal = d3.select('#svgReal');
    const svgAI   = d3.select('#svgAI');
    svgReal.selectAll('*').remove();
    svgAI.selectAll('*').remove();

    // Each panel gets its OWN projection. The left fits the real city;
    // the right fits the entire model output (which extends well past
    // Seattle's actual edge). Different scales on purpose — the editorial
    // point is "look at what the model drew", not pixel-by-pixel shape
    // comparison. Each panel carries its own scale bar so the reader can
    // see they aren't the same scale.
    const W = 480, H = 560, PAD = 14;
    const projReal = d3.geoMercator().fitExtent([[PAD, PAD], [W - PAD, H - PAD]], real);
    const projAI   = d3.geoMercator().fitExtent([[PAD, PAD], [W - PAD, H - PAD]], ai);
    const pathReal = d3.geoPath(projReal);
    const pathAI   = d3.geoPath(projAI);

    // ---------- LEFT: real ----------
    // Highlighted polygons render last so they sit on top.
    const isRealHL = (f) => REAL_BLOAT[f.properties.S_HOOD] != null || REAL_SHRINK[f.properties.S_HOOD] != null;
    const realSorted = [...real.features].sort((a, b) => (isRealHL(a) ? 1 : 0) - (isRealHL(b) ? 1 : 0));

    svgReal.append('g').attr('class', 'g-real')
      .selectAll('path')
      .data(realSorted)
      .join('path')
      .attr('d', pathReal)
      .attr('class', d => {
        const s = d.properties.S_HOOD;
        if (REAL_BLOAT[s]  != null) return 'nh-real is-bloat';
        if (REAL_SHRINK[s] != null) return 'nh-real is-shrink';
        return 'nh-real';
      })
      .append('title')
      .text(d => d.properties.S_HOOD || '');

    drawHighlightChips(svgReal, real.features, pathReal, {
      getName: f => f.properties.S_HOOD,
      bloatMap:  REAL_BLOAT,    // S_HOOD -> display name (model's term)
      shrinkMap: REAL_SHRINK,
      withMultiplier: false,    // left panel has no "×N" — it IS reality
    });

    drawLocatorInset(svgReal, W, H);
    drawScaleBar(svgReal, projReal, W, H, 2);
    drawNorthArrow(svgReal, W, H);

    // ---------- RIGHT: AI from memory ----------
    const isAIHL = (f) => AI_BLOAT[f.properties.name] != null || AI_SHRINK[f.properties.name] != null;
    const aiSorted = [...ai.features].sort((a, b) => (isAIHL(a) ? 1 : 0) - (isAIHL(b) ? 1 : 0));

    svgAI.append('g').attr('class', 'g-ai')
      .selectAll('path')
      .data(aiSorted)
      .join('path')
      .attr('d', pathAI)
      .attr('class', d => {
        const n = d.properties.name;
        if (AI_BLOAT[n]  != null) return 'nh-ai is-bloat';
        if (AI_SHRINK[n] != null) return 'nh-ai is-shrink';
        return 'nh-ai';
      })
      .append('title')
      .text(d => {
        const n = d.properties.name;
        const m = AI_BLOAT[n] ?? AI_SHRINK[n];
        return m ? `${n} (drawn ${m}× the real area)` : n;
      });

    drawHighlightChips(svgAI, ai.features, pathAI, {
      getName: f => f.properties.name,
      bloatMap:  Object.fromEntries(Object.keys(AI_BLOAT).map(k => [k, k])),
      shrinkMap: Object.fromEntries(Object.keys(AI_SHRINK).map(k => [k, k])),
      withMultiplier: true,
      multipliers: { ...AI_BLOAT, ...AI_SHRINK },
    });
    // Scale bar matched to the AI projection. Pick a bar length that
    // reads cleanly at this (zoomed-out) scale — 5 km is right.
    drawScaleBar(svgAI, projAI, W, H, 5);
  }

  // Chip-style callouts for highlighted neighborhoods. Used on both panels.
  // - On the left: just the model's name in a coloured pill (no ×N — left is reality).
  // - On the right: a small ×N pill plus the model's name beneath it.
  function drawHighlightChips(svg, features, path, opts) {
    const { getName, bloatMap, shrinkMap, withMultiplier, multipliers } = opts;
    const g = svg.append('g').attr('class', 'nh-chips');
    features.forEach(f => {
      const raw = getName(f);
      const isB = bloatMap[raw]  != null;
      const isS = shrinkMap[raw] != null;
      if (!isB && !isS) return;
      const c = path.centroid(f);
      if (!isFinite(c[0]) || !isFinite(c[1])) return;
      const cls    = isB ? 'is-bloat' : 'is-shrink';
      const display = (isB ? bloatMap[raw] : shrinkMap[raw]);
      const mult    = withMultiplier ? multipliers[raw] : null;
      const grp = g.append('g')
        .attr('class', 'nh-chip ' + cls)
        .attr('transform', `translate(${c[0]}, ${c[1]})`);
      // Multiplier pill (top), name pill (bottom). Pills are sized to text.
      const namePillH = 13.5;
      const namePillW = 7 + display.length * 5.6;
      let yOffsetName = 0;
      if (mult != null) {
        const multText = '×' + mult;
        const multPillW = 8 + multText.length * 5.6;
        grp.append('rect')
          .attr('class', 'nh-chip-pill is-mult')
          .attr('x', -multPillW / 2).attr('y', -namePillH - 2)
          .attr('width', multPillW).attr('height', namePillH)
          .attr('rx', 6.5).attr('ry', 6.5);
        grp.append('text')
          .attr('class', 'nh-chip-num')
          .attr('x', 0).attr('y', -4.5)
          .attr('text-anchor', 'middle')
          .text(multText);
        yOffsetName = 0; // name pill sits at chip origin
      }
      grp.append('rect')
        .attr('class', 'nh-chip-pill is-name')
        .attr('x', -namePillW / 2).attr('y', yOffsetName)
        .attr('width', namePillW).attr('height', namePillH)
        .attr('rx', 6.5).attr('ry', 6.5);
      grp.append('text')
        .attr('class', 'nh-chip-name')
        .attr('x', 0).attr('y', yOffsetName + 9.5)
        .attr('text-anchor', 'middle')
        .text(display);
    });
  }

  // ---- carto furniture: locator inset, scale bar, north arrow ----

  function drawLocatorInset(svg, W, H) {
    if (!_world) return;
    const size = 78;
    const cx = 14 + size / 2;
    const cy = H - 14 - size / 2;
    const g = svg.append('g')
      .attr('class', 'inset-globe')
      .attr('transform', `translate(${cx}, ${cy})`);
    // backing
    g.append('circle').attr('r', size / 2).attr('class', 'inset-bg');
    // orthographic centred slightly off-axis so PNW is recognisable
    const proj = d3.geoOrthographic()
      .scale(size / 2 - 1)
      .translate([0, 0])
      .rotate([122.3, -47.6]); // negate sign convention: rotate to centre on Seattle
    const p = d3.geoPath(proj);
    // graticule
    const grat = d3.geoGraticule().step([30, 30]);
    g.append('path').datum(grat()).attr('d', p).attr('class', 'inset-grat');
    // land
    g.append('g')
      .selectAll('path')
      .data(_world.features)
      .join('path')
      .attr('d', p)
      .attr('class', 'inset-land');
    // sphere outline
    g.append('path').datum({type:'Sphere'}).attr('d', p).attr('class', 'inset-sphere');
    // Seattle dot
    const seattlePx = proj([-122.32, 47.6]);
    if (seattlePx) {
      g.append('circle')
        .attr('cx', seattlePx[0]).attr('cy', seattlePx[1])
        .attr('r', 2.6).attr('class', 'inset-dot');
      g.append('circle')
        .attr('cx', seattlePx[0]).attr('cy', seattlePx[1])
        .attr('r', 5.5).attr('class', 'inset-halo');
    }
  }

  function drawScaleBar(svg, projection, W, H, km = 2) {
    // Pixels per kilometre at Seattle's latitude.
    const lat = 47.6, lon0 = -122.32;
    const oneKmDegLon = 1 / (111.32 * Math.cos(lat * Math.PI / 180));
    const a = projection([lon0, lat]);
    const b = projection([lon0 + oneKmDegLon, lat]);
    if (!a || !b) return;
    const pxPerKm = b[0] - a[0];
    const barLen = pxPerKm * km;
    // Top-left corner — bottom-right is taken by the figure watermark,
    // and the north arrow sits top-right. Scale bar fills the empty top-left.
    const x0 = 14, y0 = 32;
    const g = svg.append('g').attr('class', 'scale-bar');
    g.append('line').attr('x1', x0).attr('x2', x0 + barLen).attr('y1', y0).attr('y2', y0).attr('class', 'sb-rule');
    g.append('line').attr('x1', x0).attr('x2', x0).attr('y1', y0 - 3).attr('y2', y0 + 3).attr('class', 'sb-tick');
    g.append('line').attr('x1', x0 + barLen / 2).attr('x2', x0 + barLen / 2).attr('y1', y0 - 2).attr('y2', y0 + 2).attr('class', 'sb-tick');
    g.append('line').attr('x1', x0 + barLen).attr('x2', x0 + barLen).attr('y1', y0 - 3).attr('y2', y0 + 3).attr('class', 'sb-tick');
    g.append('text').attr('x', x0).attr('y', y0 - 6).attr('text-anchor', 'start').attr('class', 'sb-label').text('0');
    g.append('text').attr('x', x0 + barLen).attr('y', y0 - 6).attr('text-anchor', 'end').attr('class', 'sb-label').text(km + ' km');
    g.append('text').attr('x', x0 + barLen / 2).attr('y', y0 + 13).attr('text-anchor', 'middle').attr('class', 'sb-mid').text('SCALE');
  }

  function drawNorthArrow(svg, W, H) {
    const x = W - 22, y = 32;
    const g = svg.append('g').attr('class', 'north-arrow').attr('transform', `translate(${x}, ${y})`);
    g.append('path').attr('d', 'M0,-12 L5,8 L0,3 L-5,8 Z').attr('class', 'na-tri');
    g.append('text').attr('x', 0).attr('y', -15).attr('text-anchor', 'middle').attr('class', 'na-n').text('N');
  }
</script>
